post_text: We've had to reinvent the way we do graduation, and this year we will send our seniors off with a final victory lap at Oswego Speedway! Due to social distancing guidelines and limits to how many vehicles we can have, we wanted to share the ceremony with a livestream at 6:15 p.m. Tuesday. We'll also be premiering a video next week featuring all the graduates and speeches. Stay tuned, and congratulations to the class of 2020!

post_text:
Hannibal Central School District is closed for all students through Tuesday, April 14, 2020. All sports and extracurricular events are also postponed until further notice and we are suspending "community use" of building continue to clean our buildings.

"Legislature Chairman Weatherup, in consultation with Oswego County Public Health, declared the state of emergency at 12:30 p.m. Sunday, March 15, and issued an emergency order pursuant to Article 2B of the New York State Executive Law that all public and private schools (K-12) within the territorial limits of the County of Oswego close effective Monday, March 16, 2020, until Tuesday, April 14, due to the emerging public health threat of COVID-19 throughout the United States. This order includes extracurricular activities."

Fairley families, mark your calendars for Read Across America Week! Below are the theme days for next week, March 2-March 6:

Monday: Fox in Socks Day (Wear your silliest or mismatched socks)

Tuesday:Green Eggs and Ham Day (Dress in the color Green)

Wednesday: Wacky Wednesday (Wear mismatched clothes, clothes backward, inside-out, etc. and sport a wacky hairstyle)

Thursday: The Cat in the Hat Day (Wear your favorite hat)

Friday: One Fish, Two Fish ‚Ä¶ Day (Dress in the color Red)

ALSO there is a change in the date for Dr. Seuss night. The event will now be held March 9 from 5:30-7 p.m. at Fairley. We will have crafts, games, prizes and SNACKS! Last year was a huge success and we can‚Äôt wait to do it again! More information will be detailed in a letter sent home to Fairley families.

post_text:
Our 3rd and 4th grade classrooms are learning about the Inventive Minds competition this week. Inventive Minds is a 5 week program designed to challenge children to create an invention that solves a problem or makes life a bit easier.Informational packets and permission slips were sent home and are due back Monday. The permission slip is available at https://www.hannibalcsd.org/cms/lib/NY50000422/Centricity/Shared/Permission.2020.pdf

Details: Students meet in the Fairley library at 3:45 p.m. Jan. 29, Feb. 5, 12, 26, March 4 (inventors will need to ride the sport‚Äôs bus that leaves Fairley at 5:00 or they will need to be picked up at Fairley at 5:00.)

Students will create an invention and display board that will be evaluated on March 2nd by a panel of local judges.

Top scoring inventors will participate in the Inventive Minds Invitational with Red Creek and Clyde-Savannah Schools on March 6th at Fairley !

post_text:
Our high school library is excited to offer a limited number of Kajeet hotspots for students to sign out! These free wireless hotspot devices are for students without internet access at home and allows them to access online resources for school. They use internet content filtering and are scheduled so they cannot be used between 11 p.m. and 6 a.m.

The borrowing limit is one device per household, for one week at a time. However, these devices can be signed out repeatedly throughout the school year.

For students to use these devices, a parent/guardian must sign a consent form, which can be picked up in the library.

post_text: Some of our high school students represented Hannibal yesterday in a countywide academic competition. Students from different schools participated in activities that tested their creativity, teamwork, communication, writing and reading abilities. They were tasked with creating a story idea for a young adult book and then pitching that idea to a panel of judges acting as publishers. Each team had to create a book cover, a story synopsis, and a character portrait to support their story idea. Great job!üëçüëè

post_text: Have you heard about Dolly Parton's Imagination Library? Hannibal, along with the eight other school districts in Oswego County, is a proud participant in this early literacy effort. The program provides a free, new book each month to children from birth until 5 years old. All you have to do is register! Forms are available at the United Way of Greater Oswego County, the Hannibal Public Library or in the District Registrar's office at the Hannibal High School.

shared_text:
Center for Instruction, Technology & Innovation is with Hannibal Central School District.
October 7, 2019 at 3:52 PM ¬∑

This month, we are showcasing our CTE Computer Coding and Culinary Arts programs! Computer Coding sets the foundation of computer language including HTML, CSS, and Javascript. Students will also get to work on mobile app development, remote server workflow and data queries. The job market is fantastic for computers right now! Students in Culinary Arts get real-life experience in food preparation in a state-of-the-art industrial kitchen. Interested in learning more? Our open house is October 17 from 6-7:30 PM!
